Ford GoBike System Data Exploration¶

Ford GoBike data set includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area. Data contains information about Trips, Stations, Bikes and Users.

#----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
def new_figId():
    '''
    generate and return new uuid as figure identifier.
    '''
    return str(uuid.uuid4())

#----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
def visualize(*items, **kwargs):
    '''
    Print pandas DataFrames / figure / seaborn plot / matplotlib plot side-by-side (inline).

            Parameters:
                    *items: items (pd/plot...etc) to be displayed side by side
                    **kwargs: options (title for all, dataframes captions, captions color and size)

    '''
    options = {'title':None, 'df_titles' : [], 'df_titles_color' : 'black', 'df_titles_font_size' : '14px'}
    options.update(kwargs)
    
    title = options['title'] if options['title'] != None else ''
    table_height, df_count = 'auto', -1
    data = f'<div style="text-align: center;"><span style="text-align: center;font-weight: bold;">{title}</span></div>'
    
    for item in items:
        #print(item)
        
        if isinstance(item, str):
            item = f'<span style="color:blue">{item}</span>'
            #table_height = '95%'
            
        elif isinstance(item, pd.DataFrame):
            df_count += 1
            caption = str(options['df_titles'][df_count]) if(len(options['df_titles'])>df_count) else '' 
            item = (item.style.set_table_attributes("style='display:inline;margin-right:20px;'")
                             .set_caption(caption)
                             .set_table_styles([{'selector': 'caption',
                                                 'props': [('color', options['df_titles_color']),
                                                           ('font-size', options['df_titles_font_size'])]}])
                             ._repr_html_() + "\xa0\xa0\xa0")
        
        elif('AxesSubplot' in str(type(item)) or type(item)==plt.Figure):
            item = item.get_figure() if type(item)!=plt.Figure else item
            figdata = BytesIO()  #plt.tight_layout()
            item.savefig(figdata, format='png', bbox_inches = "tight")
            #item.legends = []
            plt.close()
            item =  f'<img src="data:image/png;base64,{b64encode(figdata.getvalue()).decode()}"/>'
            
        elif("seaborn.axisgrid" in str(type(item))):
            item = item.fig #if type(item)!=plt.Figure else item
            figdata = BytesIO()  #plt.tight_layout()
            item.savefig(figdata, format='png', bbox_inches = "tight")
            #item.legends = []
            plt.close()            
            item =  f'<img src="data:image/png;base64,{b64encode(figdata.getvalue()).decode()}"/>'
            
        data += (f"""<table style="display:inline-block; height:{table_height}">
                        <tr style="background-color: transparent;vertical-align: top;">
                            <td style="background-color: transparent;vertical-align: top;text-align: left;">{item}</td>
                        </tr>
                    </table>""")  
    display(HTML(str("<style>div.output_scroll { height: auto;  }</style>")))
    display(HTML(data))    
    
#----------------------------------------------------
def set_countplot_percentage(feature, ax, label_hight_offset = 1):
    '''
    set percentage as annotation over the bars or count plot.

            Parameters:
                    feature: column to be plotted
                    ax: axis plot object
                    label_hight_offset: amount to shift of the percent away from the bar

    '''
    total = len(feature)
    for p in ax.patches:
        percentage = '{:.1f}%'.format(100 * p.get_height()/total)
        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width()/2
        y = p.get_height() + (label_hight_offset * 1000) 
        ax.annotate(percentage, (x, y), ha='center')

For better analysis and insights, member_age will be calculated from the member_birth_year given that the data is for 2019.

In [53]:
# convert start and end time to datetime format 
df.start_time = pd.to_datetime(df.start_time)
df.end_time = pd.to_datetime(df.end_time)

# determine if trip is at day or night time
df['trip_day_night'] = pd.to_datetime(df.start_time, unit='s').apply(lambda x: "Day" if x.hour >= 6 and x.hour <= 18 else "Night")
# determine day name for each trip based on trip start_time
df['trip_day'] = df.start_time.dt.day_name()
# determine trip duration in min from duration in sec 
df['duration_min'] = round(df.duration_sec/60,0)
# determine start hour
df['start_hour']= df['start_time'].dt.hour

Dataset structure¶


The original dataset contains 183,412 trip. Features are realated to trip, statation, bike and user as shown below.

  • Trip (duration, start & end time)
  • Station (start & end station id, name, geographic coordinates)
  • Bike id
  • User (Customer or subscriber, gender, birth year)

Some feature data types need adjustment like start and end time should be in datetime format, also categoral data like member_gender and user_type would be better to change to categoral type.

After wrangling the data, only 175,147 trip will be considered in the analysis. New columns added (feature extraction) to the support the analysis, such as:

  • Trip start hour
  • Trip duration in minutes
  • Member age
  • Trip was at daylight or night</span>

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

  • member_age
  • member_gender
  • start_hour
  • trip_day
  • trip_day_night
  • trip duration </span>

In [58]:
## there's a long tail in the distribution, so let's put it on a log scale instead

# create log_duration_min in the dataframe to use it 
df['log_duration_min']= df['duration_min'].apply(np.log)

plt.figure(new_figId(), figsize=(7.5, 5)).suptitle('hist plot to visualize the dist')
hst= sb.histplot(data = df, x = 'log_duration_min');
hst.set_xticklabels([round(np.exp(i),2) for i in plt.xticks()[0]], rotation=45);
hst.set(xlabel='Duration in Minutes', ylabel='Count')

plt.figure(new_figId(), figsize=(7.5, 5)).suptitle('Box plot to visualize the dist')
bx= sb.boxplot(data = df, x = 'log_duration_min');
bx.set_xticklabels([round(np.exp(i),2) for i in plt.xticks()[0]], rotation=45);
bx.set(xlabel='Duration in Minutes', ylabel='Count', xticklabels=[round(np.exp(i),2) for i in plt.xticks()[0]])


visualize(hst, bx);

  • The average trip duration is approximately 11 min
  • The most trips took 5 to 15 min
  • There are some trips took from 55 min to more than 18 hours

Univariate Exploration Summary¶

Duration

  • Duration data is skewed to the right with very long-tail. Log transformation is used to get better visualzation
  • The average trip duration is approximately 11 min
  • The most trips took 5 to 15 min
  • There are some trips took from 55 min to more than 18 hours, whch might or might not be outliers.

Age

  • Age feature contains some outliers that have been removed in order not to affect the analysis negatively.
  • Trips took place by members under 70 only kept for the analysis.
  • Most Trips took place by members of Age between 27 and 39.
  • The Range of ages from 18 to 67.
  • The Average age is 34.

User Type & Member Gender

  • Trips by Males are around 75%, 24% by Females and 2% by Other.
  • Trips by Subscriber are around 90% and 10% by Customer.

Timing

  • Trips at Daytime is ~ 84% vs ~ 16% for Night trips.
  • Trips from Monday to Friday are nearly similar
  • Trips on Sunday and Saturday,are less than other days. This suggest that bikes are being used to commute in working days.
  • Trips Star hour are approximately between 7:00 - 9:00 am and 4:00 - 6:00 pm, Which also suggest the commuting to work suggestion.

Bivariate Exploration Summary¶


Trip counts varies with day of week, where week days trip counts are much more than trips in week ends. Also Trip counts from 12:00 to 13:00 during the week end is higher than the same time span on week days, because there are core workining hours, and we notices that members are using the bikes to commute to work. Like what is discovered previously, Male trips are more than female, Subscriber trips are more that Customer, and Daylight trips are more than night trips.
The Duration pair grid with user type, member gender, trip day of week may suggest that the duration over 100 min could be outliers. However, it will be assumed not to be outliers and will be kept.

def hist2dgrid(x, y, **kwargs):
    palette = kwargs.pop('color');
    plt.hist2d(x, y, cmap = palette, cmin = 0.5);
    ticks = plt.yticks()[0]
    plt.yticks(ticks, [round(np.exp(i),2) for i in ticks]);

g = sb.FacetGrid(data= df, col = 'trip_day', col_wrap = 4, height = 3)
g.map(hist2dgrid, 'member_age', 'log_duration_min', color = 'inferno_r');
g.fig.suptitle('Facet Grid for Age vs Duration', y=1.1)
g.set_xlabels('Member Age');
g.set_ylabels('Duration (min)');

Trip durations in weekends are slightly longer that weekdays

Multivariate Exploration Summary¶


  • In general, there is no clear dependency between feature, wher some features strengthen or weaken other features

  • The hight number of trips is taking place on Thursday by Male Subscribers of age between 26 and 35

  • The hight number of trips is taking place at 8:00 and 17:00 by Male Subscribers of age between 26 and 35, followed by trips at the same times by Male Subscribers of age between 36 and 45

  • Member of age from 24 to 32 are make trips of duration around 13 min

  • Distribution of male vs female is similar but female trips duration are shorter than males

  • Trip durations in weekends are slightly longer that weekdays

  • Males age groups are always achieving longer duration that females

  • Others age groups are always achieving longer duration than males and females except for those who are between 56 to 70 years old
  • Customer age groups are making longer duration than subscribers </span>
